import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Getting Around Korea: Transport Guide for Visitors"
  description="How to get around Korea as a visitor: the T-money card, subway and buses, KTX trains, taxis, and why you need Naver Map or KakaoMap instead of Google Maps."
>
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">Essentials</p>
      <h1>Getting Around Korea</h1>
      <p>The card, the apps, and the trains you'll actually use.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <article class="article wrap">
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Quick answer</h2>
      <p>
        Get a <strong>T-money card</strong> for the subway and buses, download
        <strong>Naver Map</strong> or <strong>KakaoMap</strong> for directions
        (Google Maps walking/driving directions are limited in Korea), and use
        <strong>KTX</strong> high-speed trains between cities.
      </p>

      <h2>The T-money card</h2>
      <p>
        T-money is a rechargeable transit card that works on subways, city
        buses, many taxis, and even convenience stores nationwide. Buy one at any
        convenience store (CU, GS25, 7-Eleven) or subway station machine, then
        top it up with cash. Tap on and off — it's cheaper and far faster than
        buying single tickets, and one card can pay for several people on buses.
      </p>

      <h2>Why Google Maps isn't enough in Korea</h2>
      <p>
        For legal reasons, Google Maps in Korea cannot give full turn-by-turn
        walking or driving directions. Use a local app instead:
      </p>

      <div class="fact-box">
        <h4>Navigation apps</h4>
        <div class="fact-grid">
          <div class="fact"><span class="k">Naver Map</span><span class="v">Best all-round; English support</span></div>
          <div class="fact"><span class="k">KakaoMap</span><span class="v">Great for transit &amp; walking</span></div>
          <div class="fact"><span class="k">Kakao T</span><span class="v">Hailing taxis</span></div>
          <div class="fact"><span class="k">Google Maps</span><span class="v">Fine for finding places, not directions</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Trains between cities</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>KTX</strong> high-speed trains connect Seoul with Busan, Gwangju,
        Gangneung and more — often faster and easier than flying for domestic
        trips. Reserve seats in advance during holidays and weekends. Regular
        (slower, cheaper) trains and intercity buses cover routes KTX doesn't.
      </p>

      <h2>Taxis</h2>
      <p>
        Taxis are metered and reasonably priced. The <strong>Kakao T</strong>
        app lets you hail one without speaking Korean and pay by card. Have your
        destination written in Korean or shown on a map to avoid confusion.
      </p>

      <h2>From the airport</h2>
      <p>
        From Incheon International Airport, the <strong>AREX</strong> train and
        airport limousine buses reach central Seoul directly; a T-money card
        works on both. Allow extra time during peak travel seasons.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="disclosure">
      General guidance for visitors. Fares, routes, and app features change —
      confirm current details with official sources such as the Korea Tourism
      Organization before you rely on them.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
